<chapter xml:id="logic_section"  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>
  Logic
</title>

<introduction>

  <p>  Logic is the study of the formal structure of reasoning. In
mathematical sciences, we use logic to construct arguments, and also to
analyze the validity of arguments.
</p>

  <p>
    In this course we consider a traditional and standard version of logic,
    which has the following basic ingredients.
    <ul>
      <li><alert>statements:</alert> declarative sentences that claim something
  is true
      </li>
      <li><alert>two truth values: </alert> every statement must be unambiguously <term>true</term>
    or <term>false</term>, but not both
      </li>
      <li><alert>connectives:</alert> statements can be combined with
	logical
	connectives <term>not</term>, <term>and</term>, <term>or</term>, <term>if-then</term>, and
	others, to form new statements
      </li>
      <li><alert>rules of reasoning:</alert> these are rules for establishing
        the truth of statements based on an established sequence of true statements
      </li>
    </ul>
We will follow the usual approach used in introductory proof writing
courses that relies on intuition, rather than a formal axiomatic
treatment of logic.
  </p>
  
</introduction>

<section>
  <title>Boolean algebra</title>


<p>The truth tables for compound statements that are presented in most
  textbooks are just input-output tables for functions, where every
  entry is a truth value. In these tables, the actual statements play no
  role; only their truth values matter. Boolean algebra provides a
  language for working directly with such functions in a way that
  bypasses the need for cumbersome input-output tables.</p>

<p>The set <m>\B=\{0,1\}</m>, together with the operations of addition and
multiplication mod 2, is called the <term>Boolean domain</term>. Multiplication
mod 2 is the same as ordinary multiplication of integers. Addition mod 2
is defined by <m>0+0=0</m>, <m>1+0=0+1=1</m>, and <m>1+1=0</m>.
</p>
<exercise>

<statement>  <p>Show that the following identities hold for <m>x,y,z\in \B</m>.
  <ol>
    <li><m>x+y=y+x</m> (the commutative law of addition)</li>
    <li><m>xy=yx</m>
       (the commutative law of multiplication)</li>
    <li><m>x+(y+z)=(x+y)+z</m>
       (the associative law of addition)</li>
    <li><m>x(yz)=(xy)z</m>
       (the associative law of multiplication)</li>
    <li><m>x+0 = 0+x = x</m>
       (additive identity)</li>
    <li><m>x1 = 1x = x</m>
       (multiplicative identity)  </li>
    <li><m>x(y+z) = xy+xz</m>
       (the distributive law)</li>
    <li><m>x^2=x</m>
      </li>
    <li><m>(x+y)^2=x+y</m>
      </li>
    <li><m>x(x+1)=0</m>
      </li>
  </ol></p>
</statement>
</exercise>

<p>  Let <m>\mathcal{S}</m>
   denote the set of all statements, and let <m>v\colon  \mathcal{S} \to \B</m>
   given by
  <me>v(p) = \begin{cases}
    1 \amp \text{ if } p \text{ is true}\\
    0 \amp \text{ if } p \text{ is false}.
    \end{cases}</me>
</p>
  
  <exercise>
    <statement><p>
	Let <m>p,q\in \mathcal{S}</m>.
	<ol>
	  <li>Show that <m>v(\sim p) = v(p)+1</m>.
	  </li>
	  <li>Show that <m>v(p\wedge q) = v(p)v(q)</m>.
	  </li>
	  <li>Show that <m>v(p\vee q) = v(p)+v(q)+v(p)v(q)</m>.
	  </li>	  
	</ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <p>The exercise above justifies the following
    associations for <m>p,q\in \mathcal{S}</m> and <m>x=v(p), y=v(q)</m>.
    <me>\begin{array}{c|c}
      \text{logical statement } r
      \amp \text{Boolean expression } v(r)
      \\ \hline
       \sim p \amp  x+1\\
        p\wedge q \amp  xy\\
       p\vee q \amp  x+y+xy
      \end{array}</me>
  </p>

  <exercise>
    <statement><p>
	Let <m>\oplus</m> denote the logical connective whose
	corresponding Boolean function is <m>+</m>, that is, we
	have <m>v(p\oplus q)=v(p)+v(q)</m>.
	Use a
	truth table to verify that a reasonable verbalization
	of <q><m>p \oplus q</m></q>
	is <q><m>p</m> or <m>q</m>,
	  but not both</q>. The connective <m>\oplus</m> is
	called <term>exclusive or</term>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise xml:id="booleanforimplicationexer">
    <statement><p>
	Find the missing Boolean functions for the logical connectives in the
	table below.
    <me>\begin{array}{c|c}
      \text{logical statement } r
      \amp \text{Boolean expression } v(r)     \\ \hline
      p \Rightarrow q \amp  \\
      p \Leftarrow q \amp \\
       p \Leftrightarrow q \amp \\      
      \end{array}</me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <aside component="instructor"><title>Summary of corresponding logical and Boolean expressions</title>
    <p> Let <m>p,q\in \mathcal{S}</m> and <m>x=v(p),y=v(q)</m>.
      <me>\begin{array}{c|c}
      \text{logical statement } r \amp \text{Boolean expression } v(r)\\
    \hline
       \sim p \amp  x+1\\
        p\wedge q \amp  xy\\
	p\vee q \amp  x+y+xy\\
	p\oplus q \amp x+y\\
      p \Rightarrow q \amp  xy+x+1 \\
	p \Leftarrow  q \amp   xy+y+1\\
	p \Leftrightarrow  q \amp   x+y+1	
      \end{array}</me>
</p>
</aside> 

  <exercise xml:id="convertlogicbooleanexer">
    <p>Let <m>p,q,r</m> be statements, and let <m>x,y,z</m>
    be <m>v(p),v(q),v(r)</m>, respectively.
<ol>      <li>
    Find the Boolean expression
      that corresponds to the logical expression
      <me>[p\wedge(q\oplus r)] \vee [r\Leftarrow p] \wedge
	\sim[q\Leftrightarrow r].  </me></li>
  <li>Find a logical expression for the Boolean expression <m>xyz+xy+y+z+1</m>.
  </li>
      

</ol>
    </p>
  </exercise>
  

  <exercise>
    <p>Use Boolean expressions instead of truth tables for all of the
    exercises in Ch 1 of <xref ref="chapterzero"/> that suggest that you
    use truth tables.
    </p>
  </exercise>
</section>

<section>
  <title>Equivalence of Logical and Boolean Expressions</title>

  <p><xref ref="convertlogicbooleanexer"/> suggests that there is some
  kind of equivalence between logical expressions and Boolean
  expressions. This turns out to be true. Here are some facts.
  </p>

  <proposition><title>All Boolean functions are polynomial</title>
    <p>Let <m>x_1,x_2,\ldots,x_n</m> be Boolean variables, and
      let <m>f\colon \B^n \to \B</m> be a function. Then <m>f(x_1,x_2,\ldots,x_n)</m>
      may be written as a polynomial
      <men>f(x_1,x_2,\ldots,x_n)=\sum_{I=(i_1,i_2,\ldots,i_n)\in
	\B^n}c_I x_1^{i_1}x_2^{i_2}\cdots x_n^{i_n}</men>
      for some constants <m>c_I=c_{i_1,i_2,\ldots,i_n}\in \B</m>.
    </p>
  </proposition>

  <exercise>
    <p>Identify all of the details for the Boolean functions in both
    parts of <xref ref="convertlogicbooleanexer"/>.</p>
  </exercise>

  <proposition><title>All Boolean expressions are logical</title>
    <p>Let <m>f\colon \B^n\to \B</m> be a function. There exists
      a truth table in whose columns are <m>n</m> statements <m>p_1,p_2,\ldots,p_n</m>
for a logical expression made using <m>p_1,p_2,\ldots,p_n</m> and the
      logical connectives <m>\sim,\wedge,\vee</m> whose corresponding
      Boolean expression is <m>f(x_1,x_2,\ldots,x_n)</m>,
      where <m>x_k=v(p_k)</m> for <m>1\leq k\leq n</m>.
    </p>
  </proposition>

  <exercise><p>Make three random strings 8 letter long using the
      letters <m>T,H</m>. Make a table whose columns are
      labeled <m>p,q,r,L</m>, and with 8 rows, filled in with the 8
      3-letter logical possiblities <m>TTT,TTH,THT,\ldots,HHH</m> for
      columns <m>p,q,r</m>, and put one of your random 8-letter strings
      in the column for <m>L</m>. Find a logical expression made
      using <m>p,q,r</m> and the connectives <m>\sim,\wedge,\vee</m> so
      that your table is the truth table for that expression. Find the
      corresponding Boolean polynomial expression. Repeat for your
      remaining 8-letter strings.
    </p>
  </exercise>
  
  <corollary><title>The connectives <m>\sim,\wedge,\vee</m> are universal</title>
<p>    Any truth table made from any number of logical
    variables <m>p_1,p_2,\ldots,p_n</m> is equivalent to the truth table
  for a logical expression that used only the logical connectives <m>\sim,\wedge,\vee</m>.</p>
  </corollary>

  <!-- further topic to develop, Pascal's triangle mod 2 as change of
  basis for two representations of Boolean functions (truth table of
  values basis versus polynomial basis)
      -->
  
</section>


<section><title>Predicates and quantifiers</title>
  <p>
    A predicate is a function <m>f\colon X\to \mathcal{S}</m>,
    where <m>X</m> is a set and <m>\mathcal{S}</m> is the set of statements.
  </p>

  <p>
    We use the symbols <m>\forall,\exists</m> to denote <q>for
    all</q>, <q>there exists</q>, respectively. It is okay to use these
    shorthand symbols for informal <q>chalkboard</q> discussion and for
    scratchwork. In narrative writing, always use words instead. For
    example, in an informal discussion, one might write
    <me>\forall x \;\; f(x)</me>
    but in formal writing, one might write
    <blockquote><p>for all <m>x</m> in the domain <m>X</m>, the
	statement <m>f(x)</m> holds.</p>
    </blockquote>
  </p>


</section>

